<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Wettability" class="currentChild" href="Wettability">Wettability</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A property of printing inks that describes the ability of the dry ink film to resist <a title="Bleeding" href="Bleeding">bleeding</a>, discoloring, fading, etc., upon exposure to moisture. An ink's wettability is an important consideration in packaging and other printing applications that involve exposure to weather. Frequently, inks are formulated with <a title="Vehicle" href="Vehicle">vehicle</a>s utilizing <a title="Varnish" href="Varnish">varnish</a>es, or printed pieces are coated with a layer of <a title="Varnish" href="Varnish">varnish</a> to increase the printed ink's water resistance. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
The term <em>wettability</em> also refers to the ease with which an ink <a title="Pigment" href="Pigment">pigment</a> can be completely wet by the <a title="Vehicle" href="Vehicle">vehicle</a>. 
</p>
